  "prompt": "How do I Integrate: 1/ (1- x^3)?",
  "response": "To integrate the function \\( \\frac{1}{1 - x^3} \\), follow these steps:\n\n### Step 1: Factor the denominator\nWe start by factoring the denominator \\( 1 - x^3 \\). Recall that:\n\\[ 1 - x^3 = (1 - x)(1 + x + x^2) \\]\n\nSo, the integral becomes:\n\\[ \\int \\frac{1}{1 - x^3} \\, dx = \\int \\frac{1}{(1 - x)(1 + x + x^2)} \\, dx \\]\n\n### Step 2: Perform Partial Fraction Decomposition\nWe express \\( \\frac{1}{(1 - x)(1 + x + x^2)} \\) as the sum of partial fractions:\n\\[ \\frac{1}{(1 - x)(1 + x + x^2)} = \\frac{A}{1 - x} + \\frac{Bx + C}{1 + x + x^2} \\]\n\nNow, solve for \\( A \\), \\( B \\), and \\( C \\):\n1. Multiply both sides by \\( (1 - x)(1 + x + x^2) \\) to clear the denominators:\n   \\[ 1 = A(1 + x + x^2) + (Bx + C)(1 - x) \\]\n\n2. Expand the right side:\n   \\[ 1 = A + A x + A x^2 + B x + C - B x^2 - C x \\]\n\n3. Collect like terms:\n   \\[ 1 = (A + C) + (A + B - C)x + (A - B)x^2 \\]\n\n4. Equate the coefficients of corresponding powers of \\( x \\) and solve the system of equations:\n   - For \\( x^0 \\): \\( A + C = 1 \\)\n   - For \\( x^1 \\): \\( A + B - C = 0 \\)\n   - For \\( x^2 \\): \\( A - B = 0 \\)\n\n   Solving the system:\n   From \\( A - B = 0 \\), we get \\( A = B \\).\n   Substitute \\( A = B \\) into \\( A + B - C = 0 \\):\n   \\( 2A - C = 0 \\), so \\( C = 2A \\).\n   Substitute \\( C = 2A \\) into \\( A + C = 1 \\):\n   \\( A + 2A = 1 \\), so \\( A = \\frac{1}{3} \\).\n   Then, \\( B = \\frac{1}{3} \\) and \\( C = \\frac{2}{3} \\).\n\nThus, the partial fraction decomposition is:\n\\[ \\frac{1}{(1 - x)(1 + x + x^2)} = \\frac{1/3}{1 - x} + \\frac{\\frac{1}{3}x + \\frac{2}{3}}{1 + x + x^2} \\]\n\nWrite as:\n\\[ \\frac{1}{(1 - x)(1 + x + x^2)} = \\frac{1}{3(1 - x)} + \\frac{x + 2}{3(1 + x + x^2)} \\]\n\n### Step 3: Integrate the Partial Fractions\nNow, integrate each term separately:\n\n1. First integral:\n   \\[ \\int \\frac{1}{3(1 - x)} \\, dx = -\\frac{1}{3} \\ln|1 - x| + C_1 \\]\n\n2. Second integral:\n   \\[ \\int \\frac{x + 2}{3(1 + x + x^2)} \\, dx \\]\n   To solve this, we rewrite the numerator:\n   Notice that:\n   \\[ \\frac{d}{dx}(1 + x + x^2) = 1 + 2x \\]\n   So, we can rewrite \\( x + 2 \\) as:\n   \\[ x + 2 = \\frac{1}{2}(1 + 2x) + \\frac{3}{2} \\]\n\n   So. the integral becomes:\n   \\[ \\frac{1}{3} \\int \\frac{x + 2}{1 + x + x^2} \\, dx = \\frac{1}{6} \\int \\frac{1 + 2x}{1 + x + x^2} \\, dx + \\frac{1}{2} \\int \\frac{1}{1 + x + x^2} \\, dx \\]\n\n   Now, split the integral into two parts:\n   - First part:\n     \\[ \\frac{1}{6} \\int \\frac{1 + 2x}{1 + x + x^2} \\, dx \\]\n     Let \\( u = 1 + x + x^2 \\), then \\( du = (1 + 2x) \\, dx \\). Thus, the integral becomes:\n     \\[ \\frac{1}{6} \\int \\frac{du}{u} = \\frac{1}{6} \\ln|u| + C_2 = \\frac{1}{6} \\ln|1 + x + x^2| + C_2 \\]\n\n   - Second part:\n     \\[ \\frac{1}{2} \\int \\frac{1}{1 + x + x^2} \\, dx \\]\n     To solve this, complete the square in the denominator:\n     \\[ 1 + x + x^2 = \\left(x + \\frac{1}{2}\\right)^2 + \\frac{3}{4} \\]\n\n     By using the substitution \\( t = x + \\frac{1}{2} \\), \\( dt = dx \\), and \\( a^2 = \\frac{3}{4} \\), we get:\n     \\[ \\frac{1}{2} \\int \\frac{1}{t^2 + a^2} \\, dt = \\frac{1}{2a} \\arctan\\left(\\frac{t}{a}\\right) + C_3 = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}} \\arctan\\left(\\frac{2x + 1}{\\sqrt{3}}\\right) + C_3 \\]\n\n   So, combining the two results:\n   \\[ \\int \\frac{x + 2}{3(1 + x + x^2)} \\, dx = \\frac{1}{6} \\ln|1 + x + x^2| + \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}} \\arctan\\left(\\frac{2x + 1}{\\sqrt{3}}\\right) + C_4\\]\n\n### Step 4: Combine the results\nFinally, we have:\n\\[ \\int \\frac{1}{1 - x^3} \\, dx = -\\frac{1}{3} \\ln|1 - x| + \\frac{1}{6} \\ln|1 + x + x^2| + \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}} \\arctan\\left(\\frac{2x + 1}{\\sqrt{3}}\\right) + C\\]\n\nwhich is the final result. Here, \\( C \\) is the constant of integration. This completes the integration of \\( \\frac{1}{1 - x^3} \\).",
